        output='# Line Items on the Consolidated Statements of Operations\n\nBased on the financial statements provided, the Consolidated Statements of Operations contain the following line items, flowing from top to bottom:\n\n## Revenue\n- **Revenue**\n\n## Costs and Expenses\n- **Cost of revenue**\n- **Research and development**\n- **Selling, general, and administrative**\n- **Restructuring charges**\n- **Impairment**\n- **Total costs and expenses**\n\n## Operating Income\n- **Income (loss) from operations**\n\n## Non-Operating Items\n- **Interest expense** (includes related-party amounts)\n- **Interest income**\n- **Other income (expense), net**\n\n## Pre-Tax and Tax\n- **Income (loss) before income taxes**\n- **Provision for (benefit from) income taxes**\n\n## Net Income\n- **Net income (loss)**\n- **Net income (loss) attributable to shareholders — basic**\n- **Net income (loss) attributable to shareholders — diluted**\n\n## Per-Share Data\n- **Net income (loss) per share — Basic**\n- **Net income (loss) per share — Diluted**\n- **Weighted average shares — Basic**\n- **Weighted average shares — Diluted**\n\n---\n\n# How Cost of Revenue, R&D, SG&A, and Depreciation Flow Through Operating Income\n\n## The Operating Income Formula\n\nOperating income (labeled "Income (loss) from operations" on these statements) is calculated as:\n\n> **Revenue − Total Costs and Expenses = Income (Loss) from Operations**\n\nWhere Total Costs and Expenses is the sum of:\n> **Cost of Revenue + R&D + SG&A + Restructuring Charges + Impairment**\n\n### Verified with 2025 Actuals (in millions):\n\n| Line Item | 2025 |\n|---|---|\n| Revenue | $18,674 |\n| Less: Cost of revenue | (9,451) |\n| Less: Research and development | (8,643) |\n| Less: Selling, general, and administrative | (2,644) |\n| Less: Restructuring charges | (487) |\n| Less: Impairment | (38) |\n| **Total costs and expenses** | **(21,263)** |\n| **Income (loss) from operations** | **$(2,589)** |\n\nCheck: $18,674 − $21,263 = **$(2,589)** ✓\n\n---\n\n## How Each Component Flows Through\n\n### 1. Cost of Revenue\nCost of revenue is the **largest operating expense** and is subtracted directly from revenue as the first deduction. It includes costs directly tied to generating revenue, such as:\n- Depreciation from capitalized launch and satellite costs ($827M increase in 2025)\n- Ground operating costs\n- Payment processor fees\n- Freight costs\n- Employee compensation (including share-based compensation — $76M in Q1 2026)\n- Revenue share and content creator fees\n\n### 2. Research and Development\nR&D is the **second-largest operating expense** and is subtracted after cost of revenue. In 2025, R&D surged 149.5% to $8,643M, driven by:\n- GPU depreciation expense ($1,673M)\n- Infrastructure and cloud computing expenses ($1,440M)\n- Employee compensation and allocated overhead ($775M)\n- Share-based compensation ($362M in Q1 2026 alone)\n\n### 3. Selling, General, and Administrative\nSG&A is subtracted next. In 2025, SG&A increased 45.8% to $2,644M, driven by:\n- Employee compensation ($519M increase, including share-based compensation of $201M in Q1 2026)\n- Legal expenses ($189M increase)\n- Marketing costs and international expansion costs\n\n### 4. Depreciation — A Critical Distinction\n\n**Depreciation does NOT appear as a separate line item** on the Consolidated Statements of Operations. Instead, depreciation is **embedded within** the operating expense categories above. Specifically:\n\n- **Depreciation in Cost of Revenue**: Includes depreciation from capitalized launch costs, satellite costs, and other production assets (e.g., $827M increase in 2025 from capitalized launch and satellite costs)\n- **Depreciation in R&D**: Includes GPU depreciation ($1,673M in 2025) associated with the build-out of compute infrastructure\n- **Depreciation in SG&A**: Includes depreciation of facilities and general administrative assets\n\nDepreciation and amortization is disclosed only as **supplemental segment information** below the income statement, not as a separate line within the statement itself. For 2024, total D&A across all segments was **$3,824M**:\n\n| Segment | 2024 D&A |\n|---|---|\n| Space | $637 |\n| Connectivity | $1,508 |\n| AI | $1,679 |\n| **Total** | **$3,824** |\n\n---\n\n## Summary Flow Diagram\n\n```\nRevenue\n  − Cost of revenue (includes depreciation of production assets)\n  − Research and development (includes GPU depreciation, SBC)\n  − Selling, general, and administrative (includes SBC, legal, marketing)\n  − Restructuring charges\n  − Impairment\n  = Total costs and expenses\n─────────────────────────────────\nRevenue − Total costs and expenses = Income (loss) from operations (OPERATING INCOME)\n  − Interest expense\n  + Interest income\n  ± Other income (expense), net\n  = Income (loss) before income taxes\n  − Provision for (benefit from) income taxes\n  = Net income (loss)\n```\n\n**Key takeaway**: Cost of revenue, R&D, and SG&A are all **direct subtractions from revenue** that reduce operating income dollar-for-dollar. Depreciation is **not a standalone line item** — it is absorbed into these expense categories (primarily cost of revenue and R&D) and reduces operating income through those channels. Only after operating income is calculated do non-operating items (interest expense, interest income, other income/expense) and taxes further reduce the figure to arrive at net income.',
