        output='Based on the provided text, here are the answers to your questions regarding satellite impairment and useful life estimates:\n\n**1. What are the impairment indicators for satellites?**\nThe company considers several specific and general factors to identify potential impairment indicators for satellite assets:\n*   **Satellite-Specific Factors:** On-orbit performance, orbit-raise timing, expected service capability, and the evolution of constellation density and technology.\n*   **General PP&E Factors:** Significant changes or planned changes in the use of the assets, technological developments that reduce the utility of existing assets, declines in forecasted cash flows, and significant negative industry or economic trends.\n*   **Operational and Environmental Risks:** Physical damage or destruction caused by space hazards (vibration, thermal cycles, radiation, micrometeoroids, orbital debris, collisions with other spacecraft), space weather events (geomagnetic storms, solar flares), and pre-launch anomalies or manufacturing defects. \n\n**2. How does the company evaluate satellite impairment?**\nThe company evaluates impairment periodically whenever events or circumstances indicate that the carrying value of an asset may not be recoverable. The evaluation methodology is as follows:\n*   **Assessment Level:** Impairment is assessed at the lowest level for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of the cash flows of other assets and liabilities.\n*   **Recoverability Test:** The company compares the estimated future cash flows to the carrying value of the asset or asset group. \n*   **Recognition of Charge:** If the estimated future cash flows are less than the carrying value, an impairment charge is recognized to the extent that the carrying value exceeds the asset\'s estimated fair value.\n*   **Income Statement Classification:** The impairment charge is recorded to cost of revenue or selling, general, and administrative (SG&A) expenses depending on the nature of the asset. However, if the impairment is considered to be outside the normal course of business (such as damaged flight vehicles, abandoned production lines, or damaged satellite hardware), it is recorded as a separate "Impairment" charge.\n\n**3. What happens if useful life is shortened - is it a change in estimate or impairment?**\nA shortening of an asset\'s useful life is generally treated as a **change in accounting estimate**. According to the text, when the company determines that the useful lives of assets are shorter than originally estimated, it adjusts the rate of depreciation to reflect the assets\' revised useful lives. \n\nHowever, if the shortened life is due to early retirement, inoperability, or damage (such as from space debris or anomalies), the company may be required to **accelerate depreciation** or **recognize an impairment charge** if the carrying value is no longer recoverable. \n\n*Note on Financial Impact:* The text highlights that changing the average useful life of satellite assets by just one year would have a material impact, affecting operating income by approximately $480 million for the year ended December 31, 2025, and $170 million for the three months ended March 31, 2026.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=25.949,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
