        output='## Impact of Shorter Starlink Satellite Useful Lives on Financial Statements\n\n### Background: Current Assumptions and Accounting Treatment\n\nPer the SpaceX S-1, Starlink satellites (reported within the **Connectivity segment**) are depreciated straight-line over **3 to 5 years** (broadband satellites: 5 years; first-generation mobile satellites: 3 years). The useful-life estimate is based on engineering studies, on-orbit performance, propellant life, and planned technology transitions.\n\nIf useful lives proved shorter than assumed, the S-1 describes two distinct accounting pathways:\n\n1. **Change in accounting estimate (prospective)** — If the revision reflects updated engineering/operational assumptions, the company "adjusts the depreciation rate prospectively to reflect the revised useful lives." This accelerates depreciation going forward but does not restate prior periods.\n2. **Impairment / accelerated depreciation** — If the shortened life results from early retirement, inoperability, or physical damage (e.g., space debris, anomalies, solar events), the company may be required to accelerate depreciation or recognize an impairment charge if carrying value is not recoverable.\n\n---\n\n### Line Items Affected First\n\nDepreciation is **not a standalone line item** on the Consolidated Statements of Operations — it is embedded within operating expense categories. Satellite depreciation is classified within **Cost of revenue**. Therefore, the first-affected line items would be:\n\n| Order | Line Item | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | **Cost of revenue** (income statement) | Increased satellite depreciation flows here dollar-for-dollar under the prospective change-in-estimate treatment. This is the primary, immediate, recurring channel. |\n| 2 | **Impairment** (separate income statement line) | Triggered only if a specific event (damage, early retirement) causes carrying value to exceed recoverable future cash flows. Classified as a separate "Impairment" line when outside the normal course of business (e.g., damaged satellite hardware). |\n| 2a | *(Alternative)* **Cost of revenue or SG&A** | If the impairment is deemed in the normal course of business, it is recorded within these lines rather than as a separate "Impairment" line — a critical distinction for EBITDA add-backs (see below). |\n| 3 | **Property, plant, and equipment, net** (balance sheet) | Accumulated depreciation increases faster, reducing net PP&E carrying value. |\n\nThe S-1 explicitly quantifies the operating-income sensitivity: *"If the average useful life of our satellite assets had been changed by one year, it would have an approximately $480 million and $170 million impact on our operating income for the year ended December 31, 2025 and three months ended March 31, 2026, respectively."*\n\n---\n\n### Differential Impact: Operating Income vs. Segment Adjusted EBITDA\n\nThe two metrics diverge sharply because of how Segment Adjusted EBITDA is constructed. Per the S-1, Segment Adjusted EBITDA = Segment income (loss) from operations **plus** add-backs for:\n- Depreciation and amortization\n- Share-based compensation\n- Restructuring charges\n- Impairment\n\n#### Operating Income (GAAP)\n- **Fully affected.** Increased satellite depreciation (via Cost of revenue) and any impairment charge reduce operating income dollar-for-dollar.\n- The ~$480M (FY2025) / ~$170M (Q1 2026) sensitivity is a direct reduction to operating income.\n- This captures the real economic cost of faster capital consumption.\n\n#### Segment Adjusted EBITDA (Non-GAAP)\n- **Largely neutralized** for the depreciation channel. Because D&A is added back in the reconciliation, the increased satellite depreciation that flows through Cost of revenue is reversed out when computing Segment Adjusted EBITDA.\n- **Also neutralized for impairment** — but only if the impairment is recorded on the separate "Impairment" line, which is explicitly added back.\n- **Critical caveat:** If impairment is instead classified within Cost of revenue or SG&A (i.e., deemed in the normal course of business), it is **NOT** separately added back and **would** reduce Segment Adjusted EBITDA. The S-1\'s reconciliation only adds back the discrete "Impairment" line.\n\nFor reference, the Connectivity segment\'s D&A add-back was **$510M in Q1 2025** and **$783M in Q1 2026** — a substantial shield against satellite depreciation volatility at the EBITDA level.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of the Differential\n\n| Metric | Depreciation Increase (change in estimate) | Separate "Impairment" Line | Impairment in CoR/SG&A |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Operating Income** | Reduced $-for-$ | Reduced $-for-$ | Reduced $-for-$ |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **Added back — no impact** | **Added back — no impact** | **NOT added back — reduces EBITDA** |\n\n---\n\n### Important Indirect Effects (Not Captured in Either Metric Directly)\n\nWhile the depreciation/impairment channel is neutralized at the Segment Adjusted EBITDA level, shorter satellite lives could indirectly affect Segment Adjusted EBITDA through **cash operating expense channels** that are not added back:\n\n- **Higher replacement launch costs** — more frequent launches to maintain constellation density (launch costs are partly expensed, partly capitalized).\n- **Higher satellite manufacturing costs** — increased unit production to replace failed/retired satellites flows through Cost of revenue.\n- **Revenue disruption** — coverage gaps from premature satellite loss could reduce Connectivity revenue, which flows through to both operating income and Segment Adjusted EBITDA.\n- **Accelerated capex** — affects free cash flow but not EBITDA directly (capex is below the EBITDA line).\n\nThese indirect effects would erode Segment Adjusted EBITDA even though the direct depreciation impact is added back.\n\n---\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nThe divergence between operating income and Segment Adjusted EBITDA in this scenario is **structural and by design**: Segment Adjusted EBITDA strips out depreciation and separately classified impairment, so the direct accounting impact of shorter satellite useful lives is largely absorbed at the EBITDA level. Operating income, by contrast, bears the full dollar-for-dollar impact (~$480M / ~$170M per the S-1\'s sensitivity disclosure). This is precisely the kind of capital-intensive, depreciation-heavy dynamic that EBITDA-based metrics are constructed to obscure — and a reason why analysts evaluating SpaceX\'s satellite economics should not rely on Segment Adjusted EBITDA alone, particularly given the Connectivity segment\'s substantial and growing D&A base ($783M in Q1 2026).\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Property, Plant and Equipment accounting policy; Critical Accounting Estimates (satellite useful life sensitivity); Segment reporting and Segment Adjusted EBITDA reconciliation; Consolidated Statements of Operations"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
